<protolog id="rid.7375_nm.330" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.330" rank="genus">Haloterrigena</organism><reference id="rid.7375"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Ventosa</surname><given-names>A.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Guti√©rrez</surname><given-names>M.C.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Kamekura</surname><given-names>M.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Dyall-Smith</surname><given-names>M.L.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Proposal to transfer Halococcus turkmenicus, Halobacterium trapanicum JCM 9743 and strain GSL-11 to Haloterrigena turkmenica gen. nov., comb. nov.</article-title><year>1999</year><volume>49</volume><fpage>131</fpage><lpage>136</lpage><source id="116">International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology</source><abbrev>Int J Syst Bacteriol</abbrev><issn>0020-7713</issn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1099/00207713-49-1-131</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">10028254</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <i>Haloterrigena</i> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><i>Haloterrigena</i> (Ha.lo.ter'ri.gena. Gr. n. <i>hals</i>, <i>halos</i> the sea, salt; L. fem. adj. <i>terrigena</i> born from the earth; M.L. fem. adj. <i>Haloterrigena</i> the salt born from the earth)</s></p><p class="description"><s>Gram-negative rods.</s><s>Colonies are pigmented red or light pink due of the presence of C5O-carotenoids.</s><s>Chemo-organotrophic and aerobic.</s><s>Halophilic requiring at least 2 M NaCl.</s><s>G+C content of DNA is 59.2-60.2 mol% (T<sub>m</sub> method).</s><s>Membrane polar lipids are glycerol-diether analogues of PG, PGP-Me and some glycolipids.</s><s>Type species is <i>Haloterrigena turkmenica</i>.</s></p></content></protolog>